ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 11 summarizes the total heat transfer characteristics of the proposed battery pack under varying ambient temperatures and discharge rates. It presents the cumulative values of total heat generation (
Q G
), indicated by a hatched black column capped by a dashed line; total heat dissipation (
Q D
), represented by wide bars extending upward from the baseline; and utilized sensible energy (
Q S
), depicted by narrower, lighter-colored bars positioned directly above the dissipation bars.

The energy balance analysis in Fig. 11 reveals that in most scenarios, the combined heat dissipation (

                              Q
                              L

                        ) and sensible energy storage (

                              Q
                              S

                        ) are insufficient to account for the total heat generated by the cells (

                              Q
                              G

                        ). According to the governing energy balance in Equation (2), this gap is filled by the latent energy of the PCM, which is utilized as the material melts. Quantifying this latent heat utilization is crucial for understanding the extent to which the system relies on phase change to manage thermal loads.
